    {
      "url": "https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/CustomerService/Documents/HOU-EO-REP-Bill-Transparency-Infographic-2026.pdf",
      "title": "250808-13_HOU_EO_REP Bill Transparency_PART2_Infographic_v4",
      "text": "## Understanding CenterPoint Energy charges on your retail electric provider’s bill\n\nWhen you receive your electric bill each month from your retail electric provider (REP), you may see charges related to CenterPoint Energy.\n\nEach REP includes a Delivery Charge on their electric bill but they are not required to outline the Delivery Charge breakdown. The Delivery Charge includes fixed charges—a base meter charge and a base customer charge—which are both standard charges applied to all active residential customers.\n\nThe Base Meter Charge covers the costs \nassociated with gathering usage data from \nthe meter and other meter costs, including \nany costs associated with: \n· Testing \n· Replacing \n· Installing or removing the meter \nThe Base Customer Charge covers CenterPoint’s \ncosts for customer service activities, including \ncosts associated with: \n· Submitting billing data to your REP \n· Call center sta ing \n· Customer educational resources \n· Programming for public safety and community support \n\nThese charges may appear on your bill as a: · TDSP (Transmission and Distribution Service Provider) charge · TDU (Transmission and Distribution Utility) charge · CenterPoint Energy charge (such as “Delivery Charge”) — the name of this charge is di erent for each REP.\n\n### Base Meter Charge\n\n#### The base meter charge is $2.79 per meter each month. *\n\n### Base Customer Charge\n\n#### The base customer charge is $2.11 per customer each month. *\n\n*As of August 2025 ©2025 CenterPoint Energy 250808-03\n\n### What’s included in the Delivery Charge?\n\n## Understanding CenterPoint Energy charges on your retail electric provider’s bill\n\nDistribution Cost Recovery Factor (DCRF) \nThe DCRF allows CenterPoint to adjust customer rates to recover costs for capital investments in the electric \ndistribution system, such as replacing aging infrastructure and improving grid resiliency. This is an interim rate \nadjustment that is filed with and approved by the PUCT, allowing CenterPoint to update rates between full, \ncomprehensive rate cases. \n\nEnergy E iciency Cost Recovery Factor (EECRF) CenterPoint recovers the costs of its approved annual energy e iciency programs with this annual charge. This factor helps fund the company’s initiatives that promote energy conservation and encourage the e icient use of electricity.\n\nNuclear Decommissioning Charge (NDC) \nThe NDC charge collects funds for the future shutdown and cleanup of Units 1 and 2 of the South Texas Project \nElectric Generating Station (“STP”) nuclear power plant. The funds collected are set aside over time to cover the \nlong-term costs associated with decommissioning these facilities. CenterPoint is the Collecting Utility for the \n30.8% Trust of Constellation Energy Generation LLC. \nBase Distribution \nThe Base Distribution charge covers the costs of delivering electricity from a transmission substation, \nthrough our distribution system, to retail customers. \nTemporary Emergency Electric Energy Facilities (TEEEF) \nThis is a temporary charge designed to recover the cost of leasing and operating temporary emergency electric \nenergy facilities (i.e., power generators) used to shorten power interruptions that may occur following significant \nweather events which cause damage to CenterPoint’s distribution system or periods of electricity scarcity in the \nElectric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) market. \n\nRate Case Expense (RCE) The PUCT requires CenterPoint to file a rate case — formal legal proceeding — every four years to seek approval for potential rate adjustments. The RCE covers the costs of the process, such as legal fees and expert testimony, and is typically a temporary charge on customer bills that is collected over a set period.\n\nIn addition to the fixed rates on your bill, your Delivery Charge includes various volumetric rates approved by the Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT). These items are charged per kilowatt-hour (kWh), meaning the amount of each will change from month-to-month, depending on how much or how little electricity is used in your billing cycle.\n\n©2025 CenterPoint Energy 250709-15\n\nTransmission Cost Recovery Factor (TCRF) \nThe TCRF is a charge that recovers the costs associated with building, maintaining and upgrading high-voltage \npower lines, substations and other related equipment that make up the Texas high-voltage transmission system. \nThis charge recovers only the costs associated with the transmission system. CenterPoint may not markup or \nprofit from this charge. This charge is adjusted twice a year in March and September to reflect fluctuating \nchanges in these transportation costs. \n\n### Here’s a breakdown of these charges:\n\nFor a complete list of CenterPoint Energy's Houston Electric rates and tari s, please visit our online resource at https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/corporate/about-us/rates-tariffs\n\nTo learn more about how these recovery charges support resiliency and reliability e orts throughout the Greater Houston area, visit CenterPointEnergy.com/TakingAction. https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/Corp/Pages/GHRI-2-0.aspx?sa=ho&au=res\n\n",
      "highlights": [
        "025 ©\n[...]\n025\n[...]\nIn addition to the fixed rates on your bill, your Delivery Charge includes various volumetric rates approved by the Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT). These items are charged per kilowatt-hour (kWh), meaning the amount of each will change from month-to-month, depending on how much or how little electricity is used in your billing cycle.\n[...]\nTransmission Cost Recovery Factor (TCRF) \nThe TCRF is a charge that recovers the costs associated with building, maintaining and upgrading high-voltage \npower lines, substations and other related equipment that make up the Texas high-voltage transmission system. \nThis charge recovers only the costs associated with the transmission system. CenterPoint may not markup or \nprofit from this charge. This charge is adjusted twice a year in March and September to reflect fluctuating \nchanges in these transportation costs. \n\n### Here’s a breakdown of these charges:\n[...]\nFor a complete list of CenterPoint Energy's Houston Electric rates and tari s, please visit our online resource at https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/corporate/about-us/rates-tariffs\n\nTo learn more about how these recovery charges support resiliency and reliability e orts throughout the Greater Houston area, visit CenterPointEnergy.com/TakingAction. https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/Corp/Pages/GHRI-2-0.aspx?sa\n[...]\n&au=res"
